Brown or yellowish brown with blurred spots on head and pronotum (
Figs. 6–8
). Mesonotum light yellowish or yellowish brown, as a rule with dark triangular spots in side angles. Forewings transparent, veins brownish or yellowish. Females usually lighter than males.

Apodemes of 2nd abdominal sternite in male longer than their width at base, usually separated by wide notch, with tips rounded, occasionally somewhat expanded and bent inwards (
Figs. 51–56
). Apodemes of 3rd abdominal tergite wide, with parallel inner margins, separated by narrow notch. The length of apodemes varies between males from the same locality (
Figs. 51–53
) and, occasionally, even in the same male (
Fig. 52
). Apodemes of all specimens on figures in the works of other authors (
Figs. 48–50
) fall into variation range of studied males from 
Kazakhstan
and 
Kyrgyzstan
.

Thus, we failed to found any diagnostic characters for distinguishing specimens from Europe (described as
S. salicicola
), Central Asia (described as
S. mesasiaticus
), and Mongolia and the Far East (described as
S. fulvius
). For this reason we share the opinion of Anufriev (1978) and regard all these forms as conspecific.
